The Meibomian glands or follicles are placed on the
beneath ocular surface of the tarsal cartilages, which are grooved
for them. They extend parallel to one another, from the
thick to the thin margin of the cartilage ; and their number is about forty in the upper, and twenty in the lower lid.
The apertures of the glands are at the posterior edge of the
free border of the lid. Each gland is a small yellowish tube,
closed at one end, and having minute lateral appendages connected with it. Each contains a sebaceous secretion, and is
lined by scaly epithelium.
