Bloodvessels of the eyelids. The arteries of the eyelids
are furnished by the ophthalmic artery, and consist of the
palpebral and lachrymal branches.
The palpebral arteries, one for each eyelid, run outwards from the
inner canthus, lying between the orbicularis muscle and tarsal cartilage,
and anastomose with the lachrymal artery. From the arch that each
and lach- forms, branches are distributed to the eyelids. The lachrymal artery
perforates the palpebral ligament near the outer part of the orbit, and
its branches supply the lid, as well as anastomose with the palpebral
branches.
rymal.
