Dissection. —A small nerve, the orbital branch of the superior
maxillary nerve, lies in the outer angle of the floor of the orbit,
and will come into view by the removal of the eyeball and its
muscles. This nerve is very soft and is easily broken. Two
branches, temporal and malar, are to be traced forwards from it,
and a filament of the lachrymal nerve is to be followed to its junction with the former. The outer wall of the orbit may be cut
