The PLATYSMA MYOIDES is a thin muscular layer, which is
now seen only in its lower half. The muscle is placed across
the side of the neck, and extends from the top of the shoulder
arises at to the base of the lower jaw. The fibres take origin from
the superficial fascia over the upper part of the pectoral and
deltoid muscles, and then ascend over the clavicle and the
triangular spaces of the neck, to be inserted into the jaw.
The lower part of the muscle is more closely united to the
skin than the upper, and covers the posterior triangle in
part, also the external jugular vein. At first the fibres of
the muscle are thin and scattered, but they increase in
strength as they ascend.
