the digastric one becomes superficial to the other. The more
superficial artery is named external carotid, and furnishes
many branches to the neck and to the outer part of the head,
viz. some forwards to the larynx, tongue, and face ; others
backwards to the occiput and ear ; and others upwards to Branch- the head. The deeper trunk, internal carotid, ascends
