The origin of the vertebral may vary in its position along the first
part ofthe trunk of the subclavian ; or it may be transferred to the arch
of the aorta, especially on the left side, or to the right common carotid
artery, when the subclavian of the same side arises from the aorta.
The course of the artery is not constant through the hole in the
transverse process of the sixth vertebra ; it may enter any other as high as the second.
The vertebral vein is superficial to its artery in the neck, and is
directed over the subclavian artery to join the subclavian vein ; it
receives the deep cervical vein and the branch that accompanies the
ascending cervical artery.
