Cervical The ANTERIOR DIVISIONS OF THE CERVICAL NERVES spring
from the common trunks of the spinal nerves in the interPosition vertebral foramina, and appear on the side of the neck between the inter- transverse muscles. Eight in number, the
nerves are equally divided between the cervical and the
brachial plexus, the highest four being combined in the
former, and the remaining nerves in the latter plexus. At
their commencement the nerves receive offsets of communication from the sympathetic, and they are further intermixed
by communicating branches.
