Phrenic nerve,
The DEEP BRANCHES OF THE PLEXUS are either muscular
or communicating, and may be arranged into an internal and
an external series.
A. INTERNAL SERIES. —1 . The phrenic nerve is derived from
the third and fourth nerves of the plexus, and is usually joined by
a fasciculus from the fifth cervical nerve. Descending obliquely on
the surface of the anterior scalenus, it enters the chest in front of
the internal mammary artery, but behind the subclavian vein.
The final distribution of the nerve is to the diaphragm. At the
lower part of the neck the phrenic nerve is joined by a filament of
the sympathetic, and sometimes by an offset of the nerve of the
subclavius muscle.
