The facial vein joins the internal jugular vein. In the cervical
part of its course it receives branches corresponding to those of
the artery.
The occipital artery is of considerable size, and is destined for
the back of the head. It arises from the carotid opposite the facial
branch, and at the lower border of the digastric muscle. From
