Piece of tympaTo open the carotid canal in the temporal bone, and to follow
the contained artery into the cranium, make the following cut
down the side of the skull : —place the saw behind the mastoid process, and cut forwards to the foramen spinosum in the wing of the
sphenoid bone (to which spot the side of the skull has been already
taken away) , the saw being directed through the stylo - mastoid
foramen, the root of the styloid process, and external to the jugular foramen and the carotid canal. When the piece of detached
bone is taken away, open the carotid canal with the bone forceps.
In dissecting the artery in the canal, large reddish branches of
the superior cervical ganglion of the sympathetic will be found
on it ; and with care two small filaments may be found, one from
Jacobson's nerve, joining the sympathetic at the posterior part
of the canal ; the other from the vidian nerve, at the front of the
canal.
