Cervical part. -In the neck the artery ascends almost in the
vertically from its origin to the carotid canal, and is in contact with the pharynx on its inner side. Its depth from the
surface varies like the external carotid ; and the line of the
digastric muscle may be taken as the index of this difference.
Thus, below that muscle the internal carotid is superficial in where it
the anterior triangular space, being covered only by the ficial becommon teguments, fascia, and platysma ; and is on the same
level as the external carotid, though outside it. But above but deepthat muscle the vessel is placed deeply beneath the external
carotid artery and the parotid gland, and is crossed by the
stylo-glossus and stylo-pharyngeus muscles with the stylohyoid ligament, by the glosso - pharyngeal nerve and its
branches, and by the pharyngeal branch of the vagus nerve.
Whilst in the neck the internal carotid lies on the rectus resting on longus
capitis anticus major muscle, which separates it from the colli ,
vertebræ, also on the superior laryngeal and sympathetic
