Peculiar- ities in length,
Peculiarities in the carotid.— The length of the internal carotid vessel varies in a given number of bodies, both from difference in the
length of the neck, and in the point of division of the common carotid
trunk. The direction of the vessel may be very tortuous instead of
being straight. It has been already said ( p. 59.) that the internal
gin of the carotid may arise from the arch of the aorta ; and further, the vessel
may be absent from the neck.- ( Quain. )
