ends
The ascending pharyngeal artery is a long slender branch of the
external carotid, which arises near the commencement of that
vessel. Directed upwards on the spinal column, between the internal carotid and the pharynx, the artery becomes tortuous near the
skull, and divides into branches for the pharynx and the cranium.
In the neck the artery gives small branches to the surrounding
