C. The SPINAL ACCESSORY NERVE passes through the foramen lacerum, in close contact with the pneumo-gastric, to
which it is united, but it is not marked by any ganglion
while in the foramen.
After leaving the foramen, the nerve gives an offset to the
trunk of the pneumo-gastric, and takes a backward course
through the sterno-mastoid muscle, and across the side of the
neck to the trapezius muscle. At first the nerve is somewhat concealed by the jugular vein, but it then passes either
