The superior or superficial cardiac nerve of the right side
continues through the neck, behind the sheath of the carotid
vessels, and enters the thorax beneath, or in front of the subclavian
artery. In some bodies this nerve ends in the neck by joining one
of the other cardiac nerves. In the neck the nerve is connected
with the cardiac branch of the vagus, the external laryngeal nerve,
and the recurrent nerve.
