The thoracic duct conveys the chyle and lymph of the Thoracic
greater part of the body into the venous circulation. Escaping from the thorax, between the subclavian artery and
the oesophagus, the duct ascends in the neck as high as the
seventh or sixth cervical vertebra. At the spot mentioned
as its highest extent, the duct arches outwards above the
subclavian artery, but in front of the scalenus muscle and
phrenic nerve, to open into the subclavian vein, rather ex- and joins
ternal to the union of this with the jugular vein. Two vian
valves guard the opening of the duct into the posterior part
of the vein, and most commonly the upper part of the duct
is divided.
