Cardiac The cardiac nerves are three in number on the left, as on
the right side, viz. superior, middle, and inferior, but they
present some peculiarities.
nerves.
Upper
Middle.
Lower.
a. The superior cardiac nerve has on both sides a similar course
in the neck ; but the left in entering the chest is between the
carotid and subclavian arteries, and parallel to them.
b. The middle cardiac nerve frequently joins the next nerve, and
passes beneath the subclavian artery to the deep cardiac plexus.
c. The inferior cardiac nerve is generally a small branch that
enters the thorax conjoined with the preceding, and ends in the
cardiac plexus.
