Upper orifice,
shape,
The upper orifice of the larynx will be seen by placing
in contact the cut surfaces. It is triangular in shape, with
the base in front and the apex behind, and its sides are
sloped obliquely downwards, in the antero- posterior direction. Its boundaries are, -the epiglottis in front, the arytæbounda- noid muscle and cartilages behind, and the aryteno- epiglottidean fold of mucous membrane on each side. This aperture
is closed by the epiglottis during deglutition.
