lamina.
The lamina cinerea is a thin layer of grey matter that Grey
extends backwards to the tuber cinereum, from the anterior
termination of the corpus callosum. This structure closes
the anterior part of the third ventricle, and shuts out the
optic commissure from that space. Laterally it is continuous
with the anterior perforated spot. In consequence of its
great thinness, this structure is often broken through in removing the brain.
