On the upper surface there are two lobes, but the sulcus
between them is not well marked. One is the anterior or
square lobe, which extends back as far as the vermiform process ; and the posterior reaches thence to the great horizontal fissure at the circumference.
On the under surface of the cerebellum, where the consurface, centric arrangement of the lamina prevails, there are three
lobes that are separated by sulci, but these are not more
distinct than on the upper surface :
viz.
biven- tral,
slender,
First, attached to the side of the pyramid, is the biventral
lobe. Next follows the slender lobe, which is connected with the
posterior part of the pyramid as well as with the other transverse
and pos- laminæ behind that body. And, lastly, comes the posterior lobe,
which joins the commissural lamina behind the pyramid in the
valley.
