anterior and
The anterior cutaneous nerves are directed outwards in the integuments in the form of slender filaments. The offset of the
second nerve joins a cutaneous branch of the cervical plexus,
and the others below supply the mammary gland and the integuments. Small cutaneous branches of the internal mammary
vessels are found with these nerves.
The lateral cutaneous nerves divide immediately into an anterior
and a posterior branch. There is not usually any lateral cutaneous
nerve to the first intercostal trunk, and that of the second intercostal wants the anterior branch of bifurcation.
a. The anterior branches bend forwards over the pectoral muscle, and
furnish offsets to the mammary gland and the integuments. The
lowest also give twigs to the digitations of the external oblique muscle.
