Dissection. Separate the subscapular muscle from the bone,
noticing the tendinous processes of origin, and observing that the
tendon of insertion is inseparably united with the capsule of the
shoulder joint. Between the tendon and the root of the coracoid
process is a bursa, which communicates with the shoulder joint.
A small arterial anastomosis on the ventral surface of the bone is
likewise to be dissected out.
The infrascapular artery, ramifying on the ventral surface of
scapular the scapula, is an offset of the dorsal branch of the subscapular
artery. It enters beneath the subscapular muscle, and forms an
anastomosis with small twigs of the supra- and posterior scapular
branches.
