Surface-marking. On the anterior aspect of the forearm are two depressions, corresponding to the position of the
vessels. The external one is placed over the radial artery,
and inclines towards the middle of the fore-arm as it approaches the elbow. The internal one is evident only beyond
the middle of the fore-arm, and points out the part of the
ulnar artery that is uncovered by muscle. The bones (radius
and ulna) are sufficiently near the surface to be traced in
their whole length : each ends below in a point, the styloid
process, that of the radius being the lowest. The articula-
