The deep palmar arch extends from the first interosseous
space to the base of the metacarpal bone of the little finger,
where it joins the communicating (profunda) branch of the
which ulnar artery. In its course across the hand, the radial
carpal artery forms the arch, whose convexity is directed forwards,
and whose position is nearer the carpal bones, and more posterior than that of the superficial arch. Having a deep
position in the hand, the arch lies on the metacarpal bones
and the interossei muscles ; but is covered by the long flexor
all mus- tendons, and in part by the inner head of the flexor brevis
