es of the
Recur- rent.
Perfo- rating.
Inter- Osseous.
Other branches
a. Recurrent branches pass from the concavity ofthe arch to the
front of the carpus, supplying the bones, and anastomosing with the
other carpal arteries. b. Three perforating arteries pierce the
interossei muscles to anastomose with the interosseous arteries on
the back of the hand. c. Usually there are three palmar interosseous arteries, which occupy the three inner spaces between the
metacarpal bones, and terminate by joining the digital branches of
the superficial palmar arch at the clefts of the fingers : these
branches supply the interosseous muscles, and vary much in their
size and distribution.
