Structure. If a piece of the middle of the gullet is coats Threeare
removed and distended with cotton wool, it will be found in it .
to consist of a muscular, a cellular, and a mucous coat.
a cular . The muscular coat is thick and strong, and consists of two Amuslayers of fibres, the external being longitudinal, and the internal coat
circular in direction, like the muscular tunic of the other parts of
the alimentary tube. At the upper part of the œsophagus the fibres
are red, and have the striped character ; but below they are paler,
and are mostly of the unstriped kind.
nal lon- The external layer is formed of parallel longitudinal fibres, which of exterform an entire covering, and end below on the stomach. The fibres gitudinal
begin by longitudinal bands opposite the cricoid cartilage (p . 125.) .
ternal The internal layer of circular fibres is continuous above with and inthe fibres of the pharynx ; these are more oblique at the middle circular than at either end of the oesophagus.
