1. The great splanchnic nerve is a large white cord, which arises
by roots apparently from only four or five ganglia (sixth to the
tenth), but its fibres may be traced upwards on the knotted cord
as high as the third ganglion . The nerve descends on the bodies
of the vertebræ, pierces the fibres of the crus of the diaphragm,
and ends inthe semilunar ganglion of the abdomen.- ( See NERVES
OF THE ABDOMEN. )
At the lower part of the thorax the nerve may be divided into large
bundles, and it may present a ganglion, or more than one on its different bundles.
2. The small splanchnic nerve is formed by roots from the tenth
and eleventh ganglia, or their intervening cord. In the thorax
it communicates sometimes with the great splanchnic nerve, and
joins is transmitted inferiorly through the crus of the diaphragm,
