Dissec- tion to reflect
- Dissection. The fibres of the trapezius are to be divided near
the scapula, and over the spinal accessory nerve, so as to trace the
ramifications of that nerve in the muscle, and its junction with the
branches of the cervical plexus. A small artery to the trapezius
(art. superficialis colli) accompanies the nerve.
The spinal accessory nerve, having crossed the posterior
triangle of the neck, enters beneath the trapezius, and forms
a kind of plexus with branches of the third and fourth
nerves of the cervical plexus. The nerve is distributed to
the muscle, and its filaments reach nearly to the lower
border.
