The rhomboideus major is larger than the preceding by
the width of three spinous processes. It arises from the
spinous processes of the four or five upper dorsal vertebræ,
and from the supraspinous ligaments ; and its fibres are
directed outwards to be fixed to the base of the scapula
between the spine and the lower angle. Sometimes all the
fibres do not reach the scapula, but some end on a tendinous
Connec- arch near the bone. These muscles are covered in part by
the trapezius and the latissimus, but a portion of the larger
rhomboid muscle is subcutaneous near the angle of the
scapula.
