The COMPLEXUS is internal to the prolongations from the
longissimus dorsi, and converges towards its fellow of the
opposite side at the occipital bone. Narrow at its lower end,
Origin. the muscle arises by tendinous points from the transverse
processes of the three upper dorsal vertebræ, and from the
articular processes of the cervical vertebræ as high as the
third. From the tendons of origin the fibres pass upwards,
the inferior more vertically than the superior, to be inserted
into an impression between the curved lines of the occipital
bone. Closely united to the inner border is the following
muscular slip : -
