The veins of the spinal cord are very tortuous, and form a
plexus on the surface. At intervals, larger trunks arise which
accompany the spinal nerves to the intervertebral foramina, and
end in the veins outside the spinal canal. Near the top of the
cord the veins are united into two or more small branches that
nation at terminate in the inferior cerebellar, or the petrosal sinuses, after
communicating with the vertebral veins.
