The LEVATOR ANI muscle can be seen now only in part,
levator and the external sphincter should be detached from the
coccyx, that its insertion may be more apparent. The
muscle descends from the inner aspect of the innominate bone
to be inserted along the middle line, from the coccyx to the
to tendon central point of the perinæum. The most posterior fibres
are connected to the side of the coccyx ; and between that
bone and the rectum the muscles of opposite sides are
united in a central tendinous line. The middle fibres are
blended with the side of the intestine (rectum). Whilst the
anterior are joined with those of the opposite muscle, in
front of the rectum, in the central point of the perinæum.
This muscle bounds the ischio-rectal fossa on the inner side.
