Origin from ribs.
The EXTERNAL OBLIQUE MUSCLE is fleshy on the side, and
muscle is aponeurotic on the fore part of the abdomen. It arises by
fleshy pointed digitations from the outer surface of the eight
lower ribs, the five highest pieces alternating with similar
parts of the serratus magnus, and the three lowest with the
processes of origin of the latissimus dorsi muscle. From the
attachment to the ribs, the fibres are directed over the side
of the abdomen in the following manner : the lower fibres
descend almost vertically to be inserted into the anterior half
pelvis of the crest of the ilium at its outer margin ; whilst the
alba. upper and middle fibres are continued forwards, the one set
