driac, lumbar, and iliac (right and left ) which lie in that
order from above downwards. The central and lower part
of the hypogastric subdivision is named pubic region, and
each lateral part the inguinal region.
Parts first seen. — On first opening the abdomen the
following is the disposition of the parts that come into view :
displace--On the right side is the liver, which is partly concealed by
the ribs. On the left side a part of the stomach is visible ;
but this viscus is chiefly beneath the ribs, and is somewhat
overlayed by the liver. Descending from the stomach is
the large omentum (a fold of peritoneum), which reaches to
the pelvis, and conceals the intestine. If the bladder is
distended, a small part of it may come into view just above
the pelvis. In some bodies the omentum is raised into
the left hypochondriac region, and leaves the small intestine
uncovered.
