more fixed in its position. The large intestine is also free
from coils, except in the left iliac fossa, where it forms the fixed,
sigmoid flexure. Instead of being a smooth cylindrical tube,
the colon is sacculated, and is marked by three longitudinal Saccumuscular bands, which alternate with as many rows of dila- with
tations or small sacs. Attached to the surface, at intervals,
are processes of peritoneum, containing fat (appendices epi- Appendploïca), especially along the transverse colon. In the rectum, in the
