The hepatic duct begins in the lobules, and its branches form
a plexus, interlobular, between them. The smallest ducts soon
unite into larger vaginal branches that lie in the portal canals with
the other vessels. Lastly, the ducts are collected into a right and
a left trunk, which leave the liver at the transverse fissure as before described.
In the left lateral ligament of the liver ducts are sometimes found
between the layers of the peritoneum ; they anastomose together and
are accompanied by branches of the vessels of the liver, viz. vena
portæ, hepatic artery, and hepatic vein.
