Seminal tubes (tubuli seminiferi ) .- These secerning tubes
are the minute branched extremities of the duct or vas defeappear- rens. They are very wavy, and are but slightly held together
by fine cellular tissue and surrounding blood-vessels, so that
they may be readily drawn out of the testis for some distance.
Their length is said by Monro to be sixteen feet, but by
Lauth to be only two feet and a quarter. The size and the
characters of the minute tubules can be learned only with
the aid of the microscope. Towards the circumference of
commu- the testis, the tubes have for the most part closed extremitions ; ties, but some communicate, forming loops or arches, and
