The PSOAS MAGNUS reaches from the lumbar vertebræ to
situa- the femur, and is situate partly in the abdomen and partly
in the thigh. The muscle arises from the anterior aspect of
the transverse processes of the lumbar vertebræ, and from
the side of the bodies of the last dorsal and all the lumbar
vertebræ by five processes, which are connected each to the
upper and lower border of two contiguous vertebræ, and to
Direc- their intervertebral substance. The fibres are directed downwards, and give rise to a roundish muscle, which gradually
diminishes towards Poupart's ligament. Inferiorly the
muscle ends in a tendon on the outer aspect, which receives
the fibres of the iliacus, and passes beneath Poupart's ligaInser- ment to be inserted behind the small trochanter of the femur,
