The LUMBAR VEINS are the same in number, and have the
semble same course as the arteries. Commencing by the union of
a dorsal and an abdominal branch at the root of the transverse process, the trunk of the vein is directed forwards with
and open the artery to the vena cava. These vessels open into the
posterior part of the vena cava, either singly or conjointly
with those of the opposite side. The veins of the left side
are longer than those of the right, and pass beneath the aorta.
Beneath the psoas muscle the lumbar veins communicate freely
around the transverse processes with one other, with the ilio-lumaround bar vein, and sometimes with the common iliac, so as to form a
plexus of veins. Issuing from the plexus is a venous trunk
process (ascending lumbar vein) , which joins on each side the azygos vein.
