The posterior ligament (one on each side) reaches from the back
of the pelvis to the bladder, and contains the obliterated hypogas- tric artery, the ureter, and some vessels and nerves. Between
these is the hollow ofthe recto- vesical pouch.
The lateral ligament, also one on a side, is a wide piece of peritoneum, that is reflected from the side of the bladder to the iliac
fossa and the wall of the pelvis. Along its line of attachment to
the bladder is the obliterated hypogastric artery.
The superior ligament is reflected from the upper part of the superi- bladder to the abdominal wall along the same obliterated vessel.
