The VAGINA is the tube between the uterus and the exterior of the body. It is somewhat cylindrical in shape,
length ; though flattened on the front and back. Its length is from
four to five inches. The vagina is slightly curved as it follows
the bend of the rectum, and its axis therefore corresponds at
first to that of the outlet of the pelvis, but higher up to
the axis of the cavity of the pelvis. In front the vagina
is in contact with the base of the bladder, and with the
urethra ; and beneath or below it is the rectum. To the side
connec- is attached the recto-vesical fascia, which sends a sheath
along the lower part of the tube. The upper end receives
the neck of the uterus by an aperture in the anterior or
upper wall ; and the lower end is the narrowest part of the
canal, and is surrounded by the sphincter vaginæ muscle. In
Lower children, and in the virgin, the external aperture is closed by closed the hymen. The vagina is surrounded by a large plexus of
veins.
