adult.
When uterine life has ceased the hypogastric artery diminishes and its
in consequence of the arrest of the current of blood through it, mation
and finally becomes obliterated more or less completely as far back of the
as to an inch and a half of its commencement, only a cord remaining in the position of the former vessel ; commonly, however, the
cord is pervious by means of a very small canal as far as the upper
part of the bladder, and gives origin to the vesical arteries.
