SUPERFICIAL VEINS. - All the veins on the anterior and
inner aspects of the thigh are collected into one trunk, that
is named saphenous from the readiness with which it is
detected on the surface.
The internal saphenous vein is the cutaneous vessel of
the inner side and front of the lower limb, and extends from
the foot to the upper part of the thigh, where it joins the
femoral vein. In the part of its course now seen the vessel,
inferiorly, is somewhat behind the knee-joint ; but as it
