The RECTUS FEMORIS forms a fleshy prominence on the
front of the thigh, and reaches from the pelvis to the head
origin of the tibia. At its origin from the pelvis the muscle has
pelvis , two tendinous processes or heads : one arises from the
double, anterior inferior spinous process of the ilium ; the other (to
be afterwards seen) is fixed into a depression on the back of
the ilium, close above the brim of the acetabulum. Fleshy
fibres succeed to the tendon, and end inferiorly in another
tendon which joins those of the muscles beneath it, and is
inserted with them into the head of the tibia. The rectus
into the is larger at the middle than at the ends ; and the fibres are
