accessory nerve of the obturator that turns beneath its outer border ; if it is present, trace out its branches to the hip-joint and
the obturator nerve. The adductor longus is then to be divided
near its origin, and raised with care, so as not to destroy the
branches of the obturator nerve beneath ; its tendon is also to be
detached from that of the adductor magnus to see the branches of
the profunda artery. Now, the adductor brevis is laid bare, with a
part of the obturator nerve crossing it to enter the plexus at the
inner side of the thigh, and with a deeper part of the same nerve
beneath it ; the muscle should be separated from the subjacent
