Acces- sory ob- turator nerve
The accessory obturator nerve * ( Schmidt) is derived from the
trunk of the obturator in the abdomen (p. 530.) and passes from
that cavity over the brim of the pelvis . In the thigh this branch
turns beneath the pectineus and joins the superficial part of the
obturator nerve : at the same spot it supplies an offset to the under
absent. surface of the pectineus, and another to the hip-joint with the
articular artery. When the nerve is small, one or more of these
offsets is wanting.
