By detaching the obturator muscle in part from
the pelvis, the branches of the artery and nerve of the same name
will be seen amongst its fibres.
The obturator artery is a branch of the internal iliac
tery (p. 554.), and enters the thigh through the upper part of the
thyroid foramen ; whilst in its aperture the artery divides
divides into two parts that inosculate and form a circle around the into two, obturator membrane beneath the muscle.
upper and lower
The upper branch extends along the inner half of the membrane,
and anastomoses inferiorly with the other. The lower branch perbranch ; forates the membrane beneath the upper one, and turns down
along the outer part to form a circle near the circumference by
uniting with the preceding branch. This supplies an articular twig
to the hip-joint. Offsets of the obturator artery are furnished to
the muscle that covers it, and some small twigs extend even to the
upper part of the adductors.
