The SOLEUS is a large flat muscle that is attached to both
bones of the leg, and terminates, like the gastrocnemius, in
the strong common tendon. It arises from the head and
the upper third of the posterior surface of the fibula ; from
the leg, the oblique line across the tibia, and from the inner edge of
the bone in its middle third ; and between the bones from
an aponeurotic arch over the large blood-vessels. Its fibres
and joins are directed downwards and outwards to the aponeurotic
part of the muscle. The superficial part of the soleus is in
contact with the gastrocnemius, and the opposed surfaces of
the two are aponeurotic. Beneath the muscle are the bones
of the leg, the deep layer of flexors, and the vessels and
below the tendon.
