Dissection. -Divide the ligaments of the ankle-joint, and separate the astragalus from the bones of the leg, to see the surfaces
ofthe bones forming the joint.
Articular surfaces. —On the tibia there are two articular
bones in faces, one of which corresponds to the end of its shaft, and
the other to the malleolus ; but on the fibula only the surface
of the malleolus that is turned to the astragalus is tipped
with cartilage. The astragalus has a central articular surface that touches the end of the tibia, and on the sides are
similar articular parts in contact with the malleoli, but the
outer one is the largest.
