kinds :
The ciliary processes are the folds or plaits by which the Ciliary
choroidal coat is terminated in front, and are arranged
around the lens, like the many petals of a flower, form- Posiing a circle (corpus ciliare). These processes lie side by
side, and consist of larger and smaller folds ; the former are Two
from sixty to seventy in number, whilst the latter do not small,
reach the free extremity of the other kind, and often blend
with the larger ones. The large folds are thin and broad and
externally at the commencement, near the ciliary ligament,
but increase in thickness internally, and projecting inwards
half the depth of the iris, end in free points around the lens.
At the posterior aspect the ciliary processes are closely con- Conne
