Structure. The iris is composed of some unstriped muscular fibres, of a plexus of blood- vessels, and of pigment cells
between the vascular twigs.
Muscular fibres. -On examining the iris with a lens after
it has been washed, its fibres will be found interlacing and
and cir- converging towards the pupil, where they are connected with
a more or less perfect ring of fibres around that aperture.
During dilatation of the pupil the radiating fibres are thrown
into a wavy state, but during its contraction they are stretched.
The involuntary movements of the iris regulate the quantity
of light admitted into the eye.
