COCHLEA. This part of the osseous labyrinth has a po- Cochlea.
sition anterior to the vestibule, and has received its name
from its resemblance to a snail's shell.
Dissection. To obtain a view of the cochlea in the dried bone,
it will be needful only to cut or file away gradually the surface of
bone forming the promontory of the tympanum, on the preparation
before used for displaying the vestibule, or on another piece of bone in which the semicircular canals are not laid bare. The horizontal direction of this body will be best seen by cutting away the
