Dissection. -The delicate internal parts of the ear, with their Dissecvessels and nerves, cannot be dissected except on a temporal bone, themin
that has been put in spirit, and afterwards softened in acid. The a fresh
previous instructions for the dissection of the osseous labyrinth
will guide the student to the situation of the membranous structures within it, but the surrounding softened material must be
removed with great care. A lens and a microscope will be needed
for the complete examination of the sacs. For the display of the
blood- vessels a minute injection should be made of them.
